Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev argued 
passionately over a range of topical subjects during a four-hour meeting.  According to a 
Thatcher spokesman, Thatcher asked Gorbachev about a Washington report that Moscow 
sold up to 15 long-range fighter-bombers to Libya, which Britain accuses of sponsoring 
terrorism.  Gorbachev did not respond.  When Thatcher accused the Soviets of not being 
completely frank about their chemical weapons arsenal, Gorbachev replied, "We have to 
try better to convince each other." Thatcher believes deterrence of nuclear weapons 
prevents war and also disagreed with Gorbachev's goals of eliminating all nuclear 
weapons from Europe.</SUM>

