SUMMARIZER="G">

Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's international admirers praised her courage and 
achievements Thursday after she announced she would resign.  Even her foes tempered 
scorn with praise for a formidable adversary. Criticism concerned the reluctance she 
showed toward increasing European unity; the Persian Gulf crisis; and the 1982 
Falklands War with Argentina.  Otherwise positive comments came from President Bush 
for being, "an outstanding ally of the United States."; France for marking "an important 
moment in the history"..of Europe"; South Africa for her opposition to sanctions on that 
country; Australia for her "courage and tenacity of purpose; and Japan for her firm 
convictions.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d076"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP901123-0062"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Former President Reagan heaped praise on British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher 
after she announced her impending retirement.  She succumbed to the challenge mounted 
by Michael Heseltine.

Reagan and the Iron Lady formed a formidable duo in the 1980s at international 
gatherings. Reagan was always grateful for her support of his conservative approach to 
foreign affairs. He sided with her on the Falkland Islands affair, and she supported him 
on the US bombing of Libya.  She backed him on her efforts to install MRBMs in Europe 
and his hard line toward the Soviet Union, and both warmed up quickly to Soviet 
President Gorbachev.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d076"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP901123-0002"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

For almost a decade, the White House regarded Margaret Thatcher as America's best 
friend whose views supported its conservative tone. She supported the US bombing of 
Libya; the Persian Gulf crisis; Reagan's free-market capitalism, hard line toward 
Moscow, efforts to install medium-range missiles in Europe, and rocky relations with 
organized labor.  This special relationship with Washington slipped when Bush came to 
power.  Mrs. Thatcher suddenly seemed to be just one of the gang.

Bush disagreed with Thatcher's decision to deport Vietnamese and Cambodian boat 
people, found German Chancellor Kohl more interesting than she did, and was not as 
warm to the Soviet leader.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d076"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA112390-0008"
