SUMMARIZER="G">

President Bush lost an irreplaceable pin supporting his mission in the Persian Gulf when 
he heard of Margaret Thatcher's resignation.  She concluded she had to go after her own 
Cabinet members told here they could not support her in her party's second round of 
balloting. A loss was expected at the next election because of opinion polls, bad 
economic news, and an unpopular new tax.

President Bush, who began his term without much trust in her, was generous in his praise. 
They had a pragmatic relationship of mutual respect and support that benefited both, 
especially after her support during the Persian Gulf crisis.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d076"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP901126-0053"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Margaret Thatcher set the example of what a woman could achieve in British society, but 
her critics say she did little else than to help women along.  Mrs. Thatcher said she 
viewed herself as prime minister, not as a woman. She was no believer in feminism and 
angered feminists by often emphasizing woman's traditional role of homemakers and 
caregivers.

Several females were appointed to junior executive posts in various ministries but only 
one served in her cabinet. Mrs. Thatcher introduced some helpful legislation: tax 
concessions for workplace nurseries; independent taxation for married women; 
legislation to compel absent fathers to pay child benefits.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d076"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA120890-0055"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Queen Elizabeth awarded former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher the Order of Merit 
and made her husband a baronet. They will be formally referred to as Sir Denis and Lady 
Thatcher. Palace insiders say one reason for the quick award was the queen's desire to 
demonstrate there is no animosity between Britain's two most prominent women, putting 
to rest rumors they did not get along.  With the OM, Thatcher can continue to serve in the 
House of Commons as the member from the North London constituency of Findley. She 
eventually should be made a heredity countess, in Britain the female equivalent to an earl.</SUM>
